1
00:00:06,000 --> 00:00:12,074
                                    
                                   

2
00:02:43,965 --> 00:02:46,024
Did you hear that?

3
00:02:46,100 --> 00:02:47,692
What?

4
00:02:56,811 --> 00:02:58,403
Say, Barbara?

5
00:03:04,652 --> 00:03:07,246
Did you...
Did you hear that?

6
00:03:07,321 --> 00:03:10,484
Could've sworn I heard whispering.

7
00:03:10,558 --> 00:03:13,254
You were reading my mind.
That's all.

8
00:03:13,327 --> 00:03:16,125
My thoughts sound like whispers.

9
00:03:16,197 --> 00:03:17,630
Oh, yeah?

10
00:03:17,698 --> 00:03:20,223
And what were you thinking?

11
00:03:20,301 --> 00:03:22,030
I love you, Doc.

12
00:03:22,103 --> 00:03:25,334
You sure make it fun to wake up
before dawn. I'll tell you that.

13
00:04:45,386 --> 00:04:46,978
Frank?

14
00:05:04,638 --> 00:05:07,630
- Did you finish last night?
- No.

15
00:05:07,708 --> 00:05:09,642
Oh, honey.

16
00:05:09,710 --> 00:05:12,736
It's a quarter to 6:00.
It's important.

17
00:05:18,686 --> 00:05:20,278
Thanks.

18
00:05:34,361 --> 00:05:35,953
That's everything.

19
00:05:38,231 --> 00:05:39,664
Helium for the balloons!

20
00:05:39,733 --> 00:05:42,702
I'm picking up a tank at Harold's
right after I drop you off...

21
00:05:42,769 --> 00:05:44,430
per your instructions.

22
00:05:45,205 --> 00:05:47,969
Did I think of that?
Cool.

23
00:05:48,041 --> 00:05:50,635
I must be starting to get
this delegating authority stuff.

24
00:05:51,712 --> 00:05:53,612
Well, Mrs. Magoo...

25
00:05:53,680 --> 00:05:55,739
I guess that's why
they made you principal.

26
00:05:56,717 --> 00:05:58,844
I guess so.

27
00:05:59,986 --> 00:06:03,422
- Honey, don't smoke.
- Come on. You're gonna make me crash.

28
00:06:04,424 --> 00:06:07,416
Look, I'll quit smokin' when you
decide to get pregnant, all right?

29
00:06:17,704 --> 00:06:19,831
Hey, guys!

30
00:06:34,855 --> 00:06:36,686
- Be careful.
- Here I come.

31
00:06:36,757 --> 00:06:38,987
Watch it.
Watch your step.

32
00:06:39,059 --> 00:06:40,993
Thanks. Okay.

33
00:06:43,930 --> 00:06:45,864
You all right?

34
00:06:47,868 --> 00:06:49,062
Hey, Jill!

35
00:06:54,007 --> 00:06:55,838
- Who's the chef?
- Oliver.

36
00:06:55,909 --> 00:06:59,072
Oh, great.
I love burnt hot dogs.

37
00:06:59,146 --> 00:07:01,114
Thanks. So when's Ben coming home?

38
00:07:01,181 --> 00:07:03,547
Six weeks, four days and...

39
00:07:03,617 --> 00:07:04,982
nine hours.

40
00:07:07,921 --> 00:07:10,082
- Watch the edges. Don't spill it.
- I got it.

41
00:07:10,157 --> 00:07:12,091
Let's take it over here.

42
00:07:12,159 --> 00:07:15,094
- Hey, Callie. How are ya?
- Frank. Good to see you.

43
00:07:15,162 --> 00:07:17,096
Hey, where's my helium?

44
00:07:17,164 --> 00:07:21,100
- Say you love me, baby.
- Not until you get me my helium.

45
00:07:21,168 --> 00:07:24,103
Righty-o.
I'll get right on it, dear.

46
00:07:24,171 --> 00:07:26,196
See ya.

47
00:07:26,273 --> 00:07:28,207
- Oh, you go here.
- Okay.

48
00:07:28,275 --> 00:07:31,267
There's Jill.
I've got those receipts here.

49
00:07:32,179 --> 00:07:34,272
- Hey, how ya doin'?
- Hey, man, how the hell are ya?

50
00:07:35,582 --> 00:07:37,846
- All right, bye.
- Bye. See you later.

51
00:07:50,230 --> 00:07:51,754
- Barbara!
- Hey, Frank!

52
00:07:54,434 --> 00:07:55,867
Good morning, Sam.

53
00:07:55,936 --> 00:07:59,099
And you must be Cindy.
It's nice to finally meet you.

54
00:07:59,172 --> 00:08:03,040
How are you today?
Shall we go in and take a look around?

55
00:08:05,178 --> 00:08:06,805
You're both gonna love this place.

56
00:08:23,730 --> 00:08:25,061
- Hey, Harold.
- Morning, Doc.

57
00:08:25,131 --> 00:08:28,123
- Hey, Frank.
- Doc, how the hell are ya?

58
00:08:28,201 --> 00:08:30,431
Headin' over to the school fair?

59
00:08:30,504 --> 00:08:33,234
I gotta go to Butler County today,
make my rounds at the hospital.

60
00:08:33,306 --> 00:08:37,299
Try this muscle machine I made,
show everybody how strong you are.

61
00:08:38,345 --> 00:08:41,803
I should probably just sit in the shade
and watch you young guys do it.

62
00:08:45,919 --> 00:08:48,479
- See ya, tough guy.
- Right.

63
00:08:55,695 --> 00:08:58,960
- Okay, thanks, Jill.
- We need finger paints.

64
00:08:59,032 --> 00:09:00,966
Okay, I'll get 'em.

65
00:09:18,151 --> 00:09:19,982
Finger paints. Okay.

66
00:09:29,195 --> 00:09:30,355
Yikes.

67
00:11:12,866 --> 00:11:15,300
Well, a civilian pilot
spots the smoke...

68
00:11:15,368 --> 00:11:19,930
and then I get here and find two
of my officers passed out like babies.

69
00:11:20,006 --> 00:11:23,271
Everything on that side
of the white line is out cold.

70
00:11:23,343 --> 00:11:26,141
So somebody starts talkin'
about chemical weapons...

71
00:11:26,212 --> 00:11:28,407
somebody hits the panic button...

72
00:11:28,481 --> 00:11:30,972
and then you people are callin'.

73
00:11:31,051 --> 00:11:34,111
- There you go.
- Look, there is no research lab.

74
00:11:34,187 --> 00:11:36,417
There is no chemical plant.

75
00:11:36,489 --> 00:11:40,357
There is no toxic waste dump.
There is no nuclear plant.

76
00:11:40,427 --> 00:11:42,588
- There's no nothin' around here.
- Okay.

77
00:11:45,231 --> 00:11:47,665
Nothing on the news channels
Nothing on the news services.

78
00:11:47,734 --> 00:11:49,895
- Nobody's got it yet.
- Good.

79
00:11:52,338 --> 00:11:55,136
I'm just gonna take myself in there
and get a look-see.

80
00:12:05,085 --> 00:12:07,019
- Hey, Ed.
- Hey.

81
00:12:07,087 --> 00:12:09,749
- That's Frank McGowan's truck, right?
- What's left of it.

82
00:12:09,823 --> 00:12:13,281
- Lucky you wasn't in town today, Doc.
- What's going on here?

83
00:12:13,359 --> 00:12:16,556
Nobody knows nothin',
not even that Fed doctor down there.

84
00:12:16,629 --> 00:12:20,793
She brought this whole circus with her,
and they ain't got a clue.

85
00:12:34,581 --> 00:12:37,812
Go on out there and see what the hell's
goin' on. Be careful.

86
00:12:37,884 --> 00:12:40,250
- Stay here?
- Yeah, we're just waitin'.

87
00:12:40,320 --> 00:12:41,810
All right, good.

88
00:13:03,243 --> 00:13:05,734
Pull him back!
Get him outta there!

89
00:13:09,115 --> 00:13:13,017
- Get him out!
- Stay back!

90
00:13:13,086 --> 00:13:15,486
Hits 'em like a hammer, Doc.
That's all we know.

91
00:13:15,555 --> 00:13:18,319
- Some kind of chemical, gas?
- No, it can't be.

92
00:13:18,391 --> 00:13:23,021
The edges of the affected area
are well-defined, stationary.

93
00:13:23,096 --> 00:13:25,394
Doc, this is Dr. Susan...

94
00:13:25,465 --> 00:13:28,025
Verner.
Like Turner, with a "V."

95
00:13:28,935 --> 00:13:31,995
Epidemiologist,
National Science Foundation.

96
00:13:32,071 --> 00:13:34,644
- M.D.?
- Yeah.

97
00:13:34,977 --> 00:13:37,036
He's breathing. Good pulse.
I think he just fainted.

98
00:13:37,113 --> 00:13:39,445
Is Midwich affected by this?

99
00:13:39,515 --> 00:13:42,040
- My hunch would be yes.
- My wife's in Midwich.

100
00:13:42,118 --> 00:13:45,576
We tried to get through for the last
six hours. Nobody picks up or calls out.

101
00:13:45,655 --> 00:13:49,216
Could somebody please get me
some blood and urine samples?

102
00:13:51,327 --> 00:13:54,262
- What's the call?
- Ninety-eight.

103
00:13:55,465 --> 00:13:57,433
You got one?
Okay, all right.

104
00:13:58,468 --> 00:14:00,902
Just take it easy.
Somebody get him a blanket.

105
00:16:06,095 --> 00:16:09,189
Barbara. Thank God.
Are you all right?

106
00:16:11,867 --> 00:16:13,926
Sweetheart, are you okay?

107
00:16:14,003 --> 00:16:17,598
- I'm cold.
- Come on. Let's go home.

108
00:17:08,658 --> 00:17:10,091
Heavenly Father...

109
00:17:11,160 --> 00:17:13,094
we mourn these lives...

110
00:17:13,162 --> 00:17:18,190
cut short without warning
or apparent purpose.

111
00:17:18,267 --> 00:17:21,600
We search for a reason
and find none.

112
00:17:23,372 --> 00:17:26,808
We have become accustomed
to the power of science...

113
00:17:26,876 --> 00:17:31,006
so when we were struck down, we turned
to science and asked, "Why?"

114
00:17:32,181 --> 00:17:34,706
But it could not answer.

115
00:17:34,784 --> 00:17:37,014
So now we turn our eyes
toward heaven...

116
00:17:37,086 --> 00:17:41,318
and seek our comfort
in God's infinite mercy.

117
00:17:43,125 --> 00:17:45,355
Let us pray.

118
00:17:45,428 --> 00:17:48,022
Our Father, Who art in heaven...

119
00:17:48,097 --> 00:17:50,031
hallowed be Thy name.

120
00:17:50,099 --> 00:17:53,193
Thy kingdom come,
Thy will be done...

121
00:17:53,269 --> 00:17:55,635
on Earth as it is in heaven.

122
00:17:55,705 --> 00:17:58,833
Give us this day
our daily bread...

123
00:17:58,908 --> 00:18:00,842
and forgive us our trespasses...

124
00:18:00,910 --> 00:18:04,368
as we forgive those
who trespass against us.

125
00:18:04,447 --> 00:18:06,711
And lead us not into temptation...

126
00:18:06,782 --> 00:18:08,716
but deliver us from evil.

127
00:18:08,784 --> 00:18:12,015
For Thine is the kingdom
and the power...

128
00:18:12,088 --> 00:18:14,955
and the glory forever and ever.

129
00:18:15,024 --> 00:18:16,389
Amen.

130
00:18:57,466 --> 00:19:00,697
Did you ever hear
of Charles Fort?

131
00:19:00,770 --> 00:19:02,635
He wrote
The Book of the Damned...

132
00:19:02,705 --> 00:19:04,798
about things nobody's
been able to explain...

133
00:19:04,874 --> 00:19:09,140
like frogs falling from the sky,
blue snow, red rain.

134
00:19:09,211 --> 00:19:11,145
Are you suggesting I read him?

135
00:19:11,213 --> 00:19:13,738
No, no.
It's just that...

136
00:19:13,816 --> 00:19:16,979
sometimes mysteries
don't get solved.

137
00:19:17,052 --> 00:19:19,213
I mean, what if something
like this happens again?

138
00:19:20,089 --> 00:19:22,717
I don't know.
What do I do? Can I call you?

139
00:19:22,792 --> 00:19:25,454
Well, of course you can call me.

140
00:19:25,528 --> 00:19:29,464
Oh, and by the way, I suggest
you read Sir Arthur Conan Doyle.

141
00:19:29,532 --> 00:19:31,796
As Sherlock Holmes once said...

142
00:19:31,867 --> 00:19:33,801
"When you've eliminated
the impossible...

143
00:19:33,869 --> 00:19:36,531
whatever remains,
however improbable...

144
00:19:36,605 --> 00:19:38,539
must be the truth."

145
00:20:01,230 --> 00:20:04,165
It's not possible.

146
00:20:04,233 --> 00:20:07,566
You made a mistake.
Do it again.

147
00:20:09,038 --> 00:20:11,802
Well, I mean, I don't have a problem
running the tests again, but...

148
00:20:11,874 --> 00:20:16,334
I have felt like this before in the
morning. It is just some kind of bug.

149
00:20:33,362 --> 00:20:35,421
Melanie?

150
00:20:50,679 --> 00:20:52,010
What's the matter?

151
00:20:57,086 --> 00:20:58,348
Maybe I can help.

152
00:20:58,420 --> 00:21:00,820
No. You can't.

153
00:21:06,662 --> 00:21:08,755
There they are!
Hey, you guys!

154
00:21:08,831 --> 00:21:11,356
We're empty!
We need some more here!

155
00:21:11,433 --> 00:21:14,561
Hi, how are you?
Oh, it's good to see you.

156
00:21:23,612 --> 00:21:25,739
Hey, Ben, this is fantastic.

157
00:21:36,052 --> 00:21:38,213
Callie, look up and smile.

158
00:21:45,795 --> 00:21:47,729
So, Ben, after a year in Japan...

159
00:21:47,797 --> 00:21:50,027
did you ever think you'd have
to get used to being a dad?

160
00:22:10,520 --> 00:22:12,112
Hello, Doc.

161
00:22:14,591 --> 00:22:16,183
I said hello.

162
00:22:18,094 --> 00:22:21,461
- How long you been standing there?
- Oh, ages.

163
00:22:21,531 --> 00:22:23,123
Liar.

164
00:22:26,102 --> 00:22:27,763
Hey, big guy.

165
00:22:33,142 --> 00:22:35,167
Why are you
kissing me like that?

166
00:22:37,246 --> 00:22:41,239
I wanted to know first,
so I used a home pregnancy kit.

167
00:22:41,317 --> 00:22:43,785
Well, honey, you know those...
those are unreliable.

168
00:22:44,554 --> 00:22:48,046
And that's why I went to see
Dr. Cornright to make sure.

169
00:22:48,124 --> 00:22:49,716
Gonna open it?

170
00:23:09,245 --> 00:23:11,076
Hi. You got a minute?

171
00:23:11,147 --> 00:23:12,739
Sure.

172
00:23:26,195 --> 00:23:27,753
Well, everything's positive.

173
00:23:28,798 --> 00:23:30,390
You are pregnant.

174
00:23:36,472 --> 00:23:38,736
We'd been trying, you know.

175
00:23:39,676 --> 00:23:41,974
Look, um...

176
00:23:42,045 --> 00:23:44,809
I wanted to tell you something
before you hear it from somebody else.

177
00:23:46,516 --> 00:23:51,010
There's a lot of pregnancies.
I mean, a lot.

178
00:23:51,087 --> 00:23:54,079
Much more than would
normally be expected.

179
00:23:55,625 --> 00:23:57,559
What do you mean?

180
00:24:00,329 --> 00:24:02,092
Well, um...

181
00:24:02,165 --> 00:24:05,362
Is something wrong with my baby?

182
00:24:05,435 --> 00:24:08,927
It's nothing to indicate that.
You're a normal, healthy young woman...

183
00:24:09,005 --> 00:24:11,667
Alan, don't talk to me
like a doctor.

184
00:24:16,312 --> 00:24:18,212
All the pregnancies...

185
00:24:18,281 --> 00:24:20,408
seem to date from
the day of the blackout.

186
00:24:20,483 --> 00:24:22,075
Oh, no!

187
00:24:34,163 --> 00:24:36,723
Dr. Susan Verner has flown in...

188
00:24:36,799 --> 00:24:39,996
This is all 'cause of
that blackout, ain't it?

189
00:24:40,069 --> 00:24:43,334
- Just come out and say something!
- They don't know for sure!

190
00:24:43,406 --> 00:24:45,966
They are all gonna be deformed!

191
00:24:46,042 --> 00:24:47,873
Why won't everyone say it?

192
00:24:47,944 --> 00:24:50,845
Wait a minute.
That's not true!

193
00:24:50,913 --> 00:24:54,872
That's... Excuse me! That's not true.
There's no reason to believe that.

194
00:24:54,951 --> 00:24:57,920
Barbara and I are pregnant.
We know how you feel.

195
00:24:57,987 --> 00:25:01,150
We know what a lot of you are thinking,
so let me say right now...

196
00:25:01,224 --> 00:25:03,715
the same thing I've told
a lot of you individually.

197
00:25:03,793 --> 00:25:07,092
The standard tests
have not revealed one abnormality.

198
00:25:07,163 --> 00:25:09,791
Anywhere. Not one.
All right?

199
00:25:09,866 --> 00:25:13,097
Let's listen to Dr. Verner, please.

200
00:25:13,169 --> 00:25:16,104
She's come to talk to us.
Dr. Susan Verner, ladies and gentlemen.

201
00:25:19,475 --> 00:25:23,536
I wanna start off by saying we are all
very concerned about your well-being.

202
00:25:26,015 --> 00:25:29,075
But ultimately it will come down
to individual decisions.

203
00:25:30,052 --> 00:25:32,213
And I understand that
these decisions will be...

204
00:25:32,288 --> 00:25:36,725
probably the most intimate,
personal, difficult decisions...

205
00:25:36,793 --> 00:25:39,227
that you ever make in your life.

206
00:25:39,295 --> 00:25:41,229
However, because your pregnancies...

207
00:25:41,297 --> 00:25:43,697
have attracted intense
scientific interest...

208
00:25:43,766 --> 00:25:45,700
including the National
Institute of Health...

209
00:25:45,768 --> 00:25:47,565
and National Science Foundation...

210
00:25:47,637 --> 00:25:51,471
those of you who decide
to have your child...

211
00:25:51,541 --> 00:25:53,566
will have all
prenatal expenses paid.

212
00:25:53,643 --> 00:25:58,080
You'll also receive $3,000
monthly as an allowance.

213
00:26:00,483 --> 00:26:05,546
If you allow your child to be
examined and tested on a regular basis.

214
00:26:05,621 --> 00:26:08,988
Is that $3,000 a family?

215
00:26:09,058 --> 00:26:11,322
What if your wife and your daughter
both have kids?

216
00:26:12,195 --> 00:26:14,220
Then you would receive $6,000.

217
00:26:20,903 --> 00:26:24,031
Look, I don't want you
to interpret this allowance...

218
00:26:24,106 --> 00:26:26,574
as some sort of a pressure.

219
00:26:26,642 --> 00:26:30,942
It isn't. It's your decision.
And if you decide to terminate...

220
00:26:31,013 --> 00:26:34,141
then of course you have
the right to do that.

221
00:26:34,217 --> 00:26:37,186
You can do it privately,
or if financially unable...

222
00:26:37,253 --> 00:26:39,585
a medical team
will be brought in next week.

223
00:26:40,656 --> 00:26:42,590
- The choice is yours.
- That's killing babies.

224
00:26:50,466 --> 00:26:52,058
Are you okay?

225
00:26:53,803 --> 00:26:55,532
Ben's moving out.

226
00:26:55,605 --> 00:26:57,937
Oh, Callie.

227
00:26:58,007 --> 00:26:59,941
He won't believe me.

228
00:27:02,311 --> 00:27:04,245
What are you gonna do?

229
00:27:05,781 --> 00:27:08,272
I can't keep it.

230
00:27:08,351 --> 00:27:10,285
I mean, it can't be Ben's.

231
00:27:11,988 --> 00:27:14,149
I just don't...

232
00:27:14,223 --> 00:27:16,157
I just don't understand.

233
00:27:18,761 --> 00:27:22,162
Something very strange is happening
to all of us.

234
00:27:24,300 --> 00:27:26,234
You know, they say the...

235
00:27:27,169 --> 00:27:29,160
the Roberts girl is a virgin.

236
00:27:32,642 --> 00:27:34,667
What are you going to do?

237
00:27:35,745 --> 00:27:37,337
I don't know.

238
00:28:37,506 --> 00:28:39,440
- You all right?
- Yeah.

239
00:28:42,712 --> 00:28:44,646
It was just a dream.

240
00:28:51,020 --> 00:28:53,011
- Let's go back to sleep, huh?
- Yeah.

241
00:29:03,799 --> 00:29:06,495
What's going on, Doctor?

242
00:29:06,569 --> 00:29:08,161
Nothing.

243
00:29:09,772 --> 00:29:12,900
They have apparently decided
to keep their babies.

244
00:29:12,975 --> 00:29:15,739
All of them? Why?

245
00:29:17,146 --> 00:29:19,740
That's a very good question.

246
00:30:30,174 --> 00:30:31,766
Nurse!

247
00:30:35,679 --> 00:30:38,671
- Keep pushing! Push!
- All right, Mom!

248
00:30:38,749 --> 00:30:40,683
Okay, here we go.
Here we go. Almost.

249
00:30:40,751 --> 00:30:43,584
Almost done!
